abstract: The bil to charter the New-York Observalory was ordered to a third reading. The Grinding Committee put forward several bills, among them the New-York Western Dispensary bill. abstract: By the way of England, we are placed in possession of our files of papers from Rio to Feb. 9, and from Buenos Ayres to Jan. 28 We add details to the telegraphic summary forwarded from Lisbon. The news from Rio Janeiro is without importance. From Montevideo, Jan. 30, we have a statement of the grounds for the expulsion of the Jesutts.

abstract: To the Editor of the New-York Times: In an editorial article in your issue of yesterday, about judgments against the City, you mention my name as one of those who have largely drawn on the City Treasury by means of fraudulent suits. Now, this does me very great injustice,as I have not now,nor have I had at a any time to which your remarks can refer. any judgments against the City.

abstract: The columns of the New-York Times, this morning, contain intelligence of extraordinary moment from almost every quarter of the globe. By the arrival of the Persia, the Kangaroo and of the Niagara at Boston we are furnished with details of European intelligence for nine days ending upon March 19, with later news from India and China.

abstract: Mr. SICKLES is busily engaged with his counsel in preparing for his defence. The impression is that the District-Attorney will have no assistance, as he needs none, the case on the part of the Government being entirely simple. The facts to be presented by the District-Attorney are few and easily proven-the fact and the manner of foe killing, and the identity of the accused.

abstract: A TOUCRING SCENE.-After his usual Wednesday evening lecture, last night, the Rev. Mr. BEECHER presented to his congregation the case of a slave mother in Virginia who had been freed with her five children by the will of her deceased mistress,-but whom the heirs, availing themselves of legal technicalities, had again reduced to slavery.
